Sushi lunch got you miso soup and a 3 piece califonia roll of avacado and fake crab meat, a 3 piece roll of tuna (teka maki), a 3 piece cucumber roll (kappa maki), and 4 pieces of assorted nigiri sushi (chef's choice). ALL roll pieces and nigiri slices were generously sized, so the price was not unreasonable for a DC lunch: $14.00  Restaurant not crowded, but service kinda slow.  Wife had Bara Chirashi over rice. She is Japanese, so she really knows her food!! She says it was delicious and had no complaints.  Then she laid the bomb on me: She said Rakuya is BETTER THEN SUSHI TARO!!!  I almost fell off my chair at first, but after thinking a minute, she's right!!  Food is a bit cheaper at Rakuya, decor is not as good as Sushi Taro, but you get more food for your money, and the quality is superb!!  Get waitresses who understand English OR Japanese and the score would be a 5.

Only downside is the price-point: expect to spend slightly more, happy hour is only available around the bar, and happy hour prices are lousy.

I planned a little food tour for my friends, and after looking at their menu I planned for us to have the chicken kara-age and the ocean spring rolls! We were not disappointed! The chicken was flavored so well and crunchy! The spring rolls were a good mix of seafood! I loved the flavor!
Great location, the bar area isn’t the biggest but it is beautiful. There is also a separate area for a sushi bar. The Kara gae chicken is hot and crunchy, super tender.
Nice restaurant across from the hotel. Has indoor and outdoor seating. Food was wonderful and the staff was great.

Excellent sushi. The volcano roll is delicious as is their (not-sushi appetizer) summer roll. Fast, friendly service and has the option for outdoor seating.  The folks I ate with say the ramen is also delicious.
Delicious food, but hard to navigate as a vegetarian.

Ordered lunch online through their website using ChowNow. Chirashi (sashimi on a bed of rice) was a lot more than I expected. It came in two parts - a plate full of sashimi and another plate full of mixed fish (cooked and raw) and vegetables on a bed of seasoned rice.  The food was fresh, prepared on time and came with all the necessary add-ons (chopsticks, soy sauce, and wasabi paste). Great place to order sushi in a pinch.
Awesome food and the happy hour is even better.

This is the single best, most authentic Japanese restaurant I've encountered outside Japan. The food was amazing, the presentation was great, and the sake was smooth. Definitely coming back the next time I'm in DC!

Rakuya has menu of many winners with at least something that will appeal to you. You can rest assured that your pick will be a quality dish. Classic dishes are given a slight twist, and you'll find plenty of Americanized Maki that are fun with friends. However, their more traditional sushi manages to be more memorable than all other dishes with its freshness and quality.

Absolutely fantastic sushi -- the best I've in DC. The other dishes were fairly good -- nothing earth-shattering -- but the sushi was excellent. Prices aren't low, but remain comparable to other sushi restaurants. Staff were kind and helpful. Strongly recommend!
Very fresh and skillfully prepared Japanese cuisine located conveniently a block away from Dupont Circle metro station.
Great sushi, but they also have good Ramen. I got the spicy miso and it was delicious.

I've only been to Rakuya twice so far, but both times have been a great success! Great menu options, seemingly high quality ingredients, and fun cozy vibes. They seem to have table space to accommodate groups up to six inside - in the summertime the patio could most likely be arranged for larger parties.  So far my favorite dish has been the sushi taro sashimi. It's of the same perceptible quality that you can get at nearby Sushi Taro (a local sushi authority that I would also highly recommend), but at a reasonable price.  Rakuya strikes a balance between good quality and borderline fine dining: unpretentious atmosphere with great grub.
I had the yakitori lunch set for about $15++ and I loved it! The lunch set comes with a side of salad, tempura, and a small bowl of udon. Do make reservations online before going.
